Currently you can use the following to map a specific require id like `'my-special-module'` to a generated source code stream:

```js
const fromString = require('from2-string');

const generatedSrc = `module.exports = ${Math.random()};`;
bundler.exclude('my-special-module');
bundler.require(fromString(generatedSrc), {
  file: '/foo/bar/generated.js',
  expose: 'my-special-module'
});
```

However, on subsequent file changes you will always get the same output from the stream, which doesn't make it all that useful for generated source code. Further, even if the code was to somehow change, it might get "cached" by watchify, which is undesirable.

It would be great if there was some clean way to define a "virtual module" that works with watchify et al. It doesn't need to be the most user-friendly API – primarily its use would be in plugins that, for example, generate content and expose it via a special module id.

For example:

```js
// generates a random number for this build
const streamGenerator = () => fromString(`module.exports = ${Math.random()};`;
bundler.virtual('random', streamGenerator, {
  file: '/generated/random.js'
});
```

I've tried to achieve this with a combination of pipeline push/unshifts, and so far haven't found any clean way of doing it. The alternative is just to push some content at the beginning or end of your bundle that is appended to `window`/`global` scope, so that the user can access it, but ideally it would be great if it was encapsulated within the bundle scope rather than accessible by any viewer of the page.

